## In the world of software, most everything takes longer to implement than you expect. And so it's not uncommon to accomplish less in a fixed amount of time than you hope.

### In a sentence (or list of features), define a GOOD outcome for your final project. I.e., what WILL you accomplish no matter what?

There will be an alerting feature installed into the code, syncing it to a device may not be possible in the time allowed, but I hope to work toward it.

### In a sentence (or list of features), define a BETTER outcome for your final project. I.e., what do you THINK you can accomplish before the final project's deadline?

With a certain downloading process, I'll be able to download the code to my mobile device and test it by inputing certain heart beats per minute/rhythm.

### In a sentence (or list of features), define a BEST outcome for your final project. I.e., what do you HOPE to accomplish before the final project's deadline?

The code is able to be linked to my FitBit for a trial run to see if it can import data from a smart watch in real time.

## In a paragraph or more, outline your next steps. What new skills will you need to acquire? What topics will you need to research? If working with one of two classmates, who will do what?

Before working on my project, I will need to gather more data on the health conditions pertaining to heart rhythms and beats per minute and how they have been and 
could possibly be tracked.  I will need to learn how to set proper parameters in code.  In working with multiple inputs, I will need to practice my file derivation skills
to be able to call upon and import data (heart rhythms).  If I am not able to do this in real time, I could use a project such as the data collector where the user inputs their
heart rhythm for the day in a data sheet, the program reads it, and gives an evaluation as to their progress and any possible alerts for upcoming seizures/health issues
by the rhythms fluctuations throughout the day.  I will need to research the effectiveness of this method vs. real time.  Additionally, I will continue to research the code used in present heart
monitors and the alterations I'd be doing with my new device/program.
